<DOC><DOCNO> AP891007-0022 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-89 0149EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     10-07 0556</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,550</SECOND><HEAD>EPA Issues Largest-Ever Toxic Waste Fine</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Environmental Protection Agency is fininga California company $6.2 million for allegedly storing more toxicwastes than it was authorized to handle.   The civil penalty, the largest fine ever under federal toxicwaste disposal laws, was levied Friday against Casmalia Resourcesof Casmalia, Calif., operator of a hazardous waste treatment,storage and disposal facility.   The EPA accused Casmalia Resources of ``accepting more hazardouswaste materials than its existing landfills were authorized tohandle.''   The company also was charged with violating federal toxic wasteregulations because it improperly expanded its existing landfillsto accommodate additional wastes.   EPA spokeswoman Robin Woods said the company must pay the finewithin 30 days or appeal.   Before Friday's action, the largest penalty obtained by the EPAfor violation of the federal law governing toxic waste disposal was$2.78 million last March against the Four County Landfill inRochester, Ind. That penalty came as a result of a federal judge'sruling in a civil suit.</TEXT><NOTE>Bush Makes History By Visiting Senate Floor</NOTE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush made a little history bywalking on to the Senate floor for a few seconds.   Senate associate historian Don Ritchie said there's no record ofany sitting president making an informal visit to the floor,although presidents have given formal addresses in the Senatechamber.   Normally, presidents speak in the larger House chamber to ajoint session of Congress.   Bush decided to visit the floor after private meetings withSenate Republicans and Majority Leader George J. Mitchell, D-Maine.He walked through the door to a round of applause from the handfulof senators on the floor and the mostly empty spectator gallery.   The visit ended in less than a minute.   Ritchie said Woodrow Wilson, Herbert Hoover, Richard Nixon andGerald Ford spoke in the Senate chamber during their presidencies.Harry Truman and Ford visited the floor after their terms had ended.</TEXT><NOTE>Bush to Host Margaret Thatcher at Camp David Next Month</NOTE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush and British Prime MinisterMargaret Thatcher will hold informal talks Nov. 24 at Camp David,the presidential retreat in Maryland's Catoctin Mountains, theWhite House says.   The meeting, a day after Thanksgiving, will be Bush's firstdiscussions with Mrs. Thatcher since the seven-nation economicsummit in Paris last July.   Mrs. Thatcher also visited Camp David for talks with PresidentReagan.</TEXT><NOTE>Soviet Defense Minister Invites Cheney to Moscow</NOTE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney has aninvitation to visit the Soviet Union.   Soviet Defense Minister Dimitri Yazov ended his first U.S. visitFriday by inviting Cheney to Moscow, praising American soldiers andbragging about the impenetrability of his country's air defensesystem.   Yazov and appeared at a joint news conference where they pledgeda continuation of military exchanges, but made no substantiveannouncements.   Cheney, who said he would visit the Soviet Union at ayet-to-be-decided time, said the military-to-military contactsbetween the two superpower defense chiefs were ``very productive.''   During the week, Yazov visited Camp Pendleton, a Marine trainingbase north of San Diego; Luke Air Force Base in Arizona; and FortBragg, home of the Army's 82nd Airborne in Fayetteville, N.C.   What impressed him most, Yazov said, were the soldiers _``dedicated young men'' with a ``high level of training.''</TEXT></DOC>